Title: Student Spending Habits Dataset Description: This dataset contains fictional data representing the spending habits of 1000 students across various demographic groups and academic backgrounds. The dataset includes information such as age, gender, year in school, major, monthly income, financial aid received, and expenses in different spending categories. Spending categories include tuition, housing, food, transportation, books & supplies, entertainment, personal care, technology, health & wellness, and miscellaneous expenses. Additionally, the dataset includes the preferred payment method for each student. Columns:

Age: Age of the student (in years) Gender: Gender of the student (Male, Female, Non-binary) Year in School: Year of study (Freshman, Sophomore, Junior, Senior) Major: Field of study or major Monthly Income: Monthly income of the student (in dollars) Financial Aid: Financial aid received by the student (in dollars) Tuition: Expenses for tuition (in dollars) Housing: Expenses for housing (in dollars) Food: Expenses for food (in dollars) Transportation: Expenses for transportation (in dollars) Books & Supplies: Expenses for books and supplies (in dollars) Entertainment: Expenses for entertainment (in dollars) Personal Care: Expenses for personal care items (in dollars) Technology: Expenses for technology (in dollars) Health & Wellness: Expenses for health and wellness (in dollars) Miscellaneous: Miscellaneous expenses (in dollars) Preferred Payment Method: Preferred payment method (Cash, Credit/Debit Card, Mobile Payment App) Usage: This dataset can be used for various analyses related to student spending habits, financial literacy, budgeting strategies, and payment preferences. Researchers, educators, and students can utilize this dataset for exploratory data analysis, predictive modeling, and developing insights into the financial behaviors of students. Acknowledgements: This dataset was generated for educational and research purposes, and all data is entirely fictional.

# Hunting for outliers

numeric_columns = ['age', 'monthly_income', 'financial_aid', 'tuition', 'housing', 'food',
                    'transportation', 'books_supplies', 'entertainment', 'personal_care',
                    'technology', 'health_wellness', 'miscellaneous']

# IQR method
Q1 = df[numeric_columns].quantile(0.25)
Q3 = df[numeric_columns].quantile(0.75)
IQR = Q3 - Q1
outliers_iqr = ((df[numeric_columns] < (Q1 - 1.5 * IQR)) | (df[numeric_columns] > (Q3 + 1.5 * IQR)))

# Displaying the outliers
print("\nOutliers (IQR Method):")
print(outliers_iqr.sum())
print("\nNo magical outliers detected! Our data enchantment is working its wonders. 🪄🌟")

from tabulate import tabulate

def column_info_table(df):
    # Create a DataFrame with column information
    table_df = pd.DataFrame({
        'Column Name': df.columns,
        'Data Type': df.dtypes.values,
        'Number of Unique Values': df.nunique().values,
        'Unique Values': [df[column].unique()[:5] for column in df.columns]
    })

    return table_df

# Assuming df is your DataFrame
result_table = column_info_table(df)

# Display the table using tabulate
print(tabulate(result_table, headers='keys', tablefmt='pretty'))

# Select additional columns for histograms
selected_columns = ['monthly_income', 'financial_aid', 'tuition', 'housing', 'entertainment', 'transportation']

# Determine the number of rows and columns for subplots
num_rows = len(selected_columns) // 2 + len(selected_columns) % 2
num_cols = 2

# Set up subplots
fig, axes = plt.subplots(num_rows, num_cols, figsize=(12, 3 * num_rows))

# Flatten the axes array for easy iteration
axes = axes.flatten()

# Plot histograms for each selected column
for i, column in enumerate(selected_columns):
    sns.histplot(df[column], bins=20, kde=True, ax=axes[i], color='skyblue')
    
    # Add numbers on top of each bar
    for rect in axes[i].patches:
        height = rect.get_height()
        axes[i].text(rect.get_x() + rect.get_width() / 2, height, f'{int(height)}', ha='center', va='bottom', fontsize=8)

    axes[i].set_title(f'Distribution of {column}')
    axes[i].set_xlabel(column)
    axes[i].set_ylabel('Frequency')

# Adjust layout to prevent overlapping
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

What do you see here?

Examining the monthly income distribution, a significant cluster emerges between 1200 and 1400, whereas the narrower range of 600 to 800 exhibits less fluctuation. The key insight is that the predominant income bracket lies just below 1200, extending up to approximately 1400. You can apply a similar analysis to the remaining distributions.

Now, imagine the dataset as a meticulously designed structure, much like a well-organized landscape. By comprehensively understanding its layout, you'll find yourself equipped to navigate through its details and complexities, paving the way for insightful analysis and interpretation.

At an average age of 21, our audience is already accustomed to electronic payments, making it effortlessly convenient to introduce additional incentives for this payment method. A strategic approach to encourage electronic payments could yield favorable outcomes.

With an average monthly income of around $1,000, students allocate a significant portion to transportation and school-related expenses. Focusing on these categories for electronic payment incentives could enhance user adoption with targeted encouragement.

Engineering and computer science students exhibit a neutral preference for payment methods, providing an opportunity for targeted efforts to promote electronic payment adoption among this group.

The third year (junior) stands out as the peak for study expenses, presenting an opportunity to focus efforts on this academic level for targeted interventions.
